<br>
Determined to not make the same mistake again, I tried an enchanter.  Everyone loves them, and they get group easily (well, atleast as soon as you reach 16.. soloing before that time).  Played the class grouped all the way to 60 in like half the time it took my mage to get 51.  Then I found out that at raids enchanters are nothing more than buffers.. no more crowd control, no more keeping that pet charmed to do extra damage.. the challenge is gone.<br>
<br>
Being a bit more aware of what the high end game looked, I decide on playing a rogue.  I liked that alot, but it was quite a bit harder to get a group than with my enchanter, mainly because rogues don't do anything that's really essential in a fast paced dungeon group (ie, tank, snare, heal, evac, mana regen, slow or crowd control -- note that mages don't either).  In other words, if you're lacking any of the above, you don't get a damage dealer.<br>
<br>
Dunno exactly why I tried the monk, but before my rogue was 50, I tried a monk.  I was very impressed.  I loved cabillis (my first iksar), loved mend, and loved the fact I could do things with almost no gear at all (was only at level 20 orso before I did some twinking, as I decided I liked the class a lot).  Grouping wasn't essential, but neither was it impossible, perfect!  I could function as emergency tank in groups (before uber gear, our low hitpoints make us inefficient to heal), but I never thought of myself as the main tank, not even in groups I formed myself.  <br>
<br>
Needless to say, the monk was 60 way before my rogue (still not 60), and I never regretted it.  I still don't regret it, however the recent nerf has taken a lot of fun out of the game for me.  Getting nerfed accross the board, for no other reason that VI screwed up on all/all gear and some warriors whining that they suck is ludicrous.  <br>
<br>
I see no reason why only people that can soak up lots of damage wearing plate are supposed to be the best tanks in ALL cases.  I can make an equally valid point that someone who's almost nekkid and can dodge blows almost faster than the eye can see (hey, if plate can absorb and even dodge blows from AoW, then I can dodge faster than the eye can see) wouldn't tank BETTER in SOME situations.<br>
<br>
But VI is unfortunately blind.  Instead of spreading the burden amongst classes to create more diversity, they focus on this &quot;1 class has to be best at something ALL of the time&quot; thing:<br>
<br>
Warrior - tanking<br>
Cleric - healing<br>
Shaman - slowing &amp; stat buffing<br>
Wizards - nuking<br>
Necro - dots<br>
Enchanter - speed &amp; mana buf<br>
<br>
Don't think there are any other classes that are better at something in all cases, except perhaps for some minor buffs or very situational skill.  Rogues can be beat by Rangers at damage dealing.  For pulling rangers, bards, sk's and monks all are used in different situations.<br>
<br>
Verant sticks pretty hard to the above list though, with only minor exceptions.  If I was designing the classes, I'd have ensured that classes are still very interdependant, but at the same time, no class would be the best at anything in more than 90% of the cases.  I'd spread debuffs around a bit better; currently only Slow has any real effect on a mob, I'd prolly make Slow less effective, but enhance the effectiveness of another debuff (Weakness or Cripple) to achieve the same total effect.  ie, the mob hits faster because it isn't slowed as much, but thanks to Weakness it hits less hard when it does, giving the same total effect as currently the single 75% slow spell would have in damage reduction.<br>
<br>
I'd create more mobs that are only viable to be killed if you have lots of nukers (like Sontalak).  I'd create more mobs that dodge almost all blows or are nearly immune to melee, yet are easily nuked down.  I'd create mobs that hit so fast that you need a high mitigation tank as dodging blows is not viable (assuming there's a limit how fast you can dodge blows -- that would be realistic).  And the other way around, mobs that hit so hard but slow, that dodging the blows is the only realistic solution.  This could even be a racial difference amongst tanks, ie, the gnome warrior dodges more, and the ogre warriors absorbs better, making them slightly better tanks in specific situations, but never overly preferred over the other for any situation.<br>
<br>
In other words, I'd be in favor for more variation, instead of: &quot;stick plate tank infront of mob, and keep him/her upright while 50 other people beat it up with the mob never as much as flinching at them&quot;.  <br>
<br>
